<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "Does this tool upload my images to a server?", answer: "No. This image resizer works entirely in your browser using the HTML5 Canvas API. Your images are never uploaded to any server, making it completely private and secure. The image data stays on your device throughout the entire process, from loading to resizing to downloading. This means you can safely resize sensitive or confidential images without worrying about data privacy." },
  { question: "What image formats are supported?", answer: "You can upload images in any format supported by your browser, including JPEG, PNG, GIF, WebP, BMP, and SVG. For output, you can choose between three formats: PNG (lossless, larger files, supports transparency), JPEG (lossy compression with adjustable quality, smaller files, no transparency), and WebP (modern format with excellent compression, supports both lossy and lossless, supported by all major browsers). Choose PNG for graphics with text or transparency, JPEG for photographs, and WebP for the best size-to-quality ratio." },
  { question: "How does the quality slider work?", answer: "The quality slider controls the compression level for JPEG and WebP output formats. A value of 100 means maximum quality with minimal compression, while lower values reduce file size at the cost of image quality. For JPEG, a quality of 80-85 is typically a good balance between quality and file size. For WebP, you can often go as low as 75 while maintaining excellent visual quality. The quality slider has no effect when PNG is selected as the output format because PNG uses lossless compression. The estimated file size updates when you resize, letting you see the impact of quality changes." },
  { question: "What does 'maintain aspect ratio' mean?", answer: "Aspect ratio is the proportional relationship between an image's width and height. When 'Maintain Aspect Ratio' is checked, changing the width automatically calculates the corresponding height (and vice versa) to preserve the original proportions. This prevents the image from being stretched or squished. For example, if the original image is 1920x1080 (16:9 ratio) and you set the width to 960, the height will automatically be set to 540 to maintain the same 16:9 ratio." },
  { question: "What is the maximum image size I can resize?", answer: "The maximum dimensions depend on your browser and device memory. Most modern browsers can handle canvas dimensions up to 16,384 x 16,384 pixels, though practical limits may be lower on mobile devices. For best performance, keep dimensions under 10,000 pixels on each side. The tool itself limits the target dimensions to 10,000 x 10,000 pixels. There is no file size limit for input images, but very large images (over 50 MB) may take a moment to load depending on your device's processing power." }
]) %>

